<p>The <code>in</code> function tests if a value is in a comma-separated list.</p>

<h2>Basic Usage</h2>
<pre>{open}if {open}echo 'apple' | in('apple,banana,cherry'){close} eq 1{close}Found{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if {echo 'apple' | in('apple,banana,cherry')} eq 1}<p>Result: <b>apple is in the list</b></p>{/if}

<h2>Not Found</h2>
<pre>{open}if {open}echo 'grape' | in('apple,banana,cherry'){close} eq 0{close}Not in list{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if {echo 'grape' | in('apple,banana,cherry')} eq 0}<p>Result: <b>grape is NOT in the list</b></p>{/if}

<h2>With Variable</h2>
{data $fruit = 'banana'}
<pre>{open}data $fruit = 'banana'{close}
{open}if {open}echo $fruit | in('apple,banana,cherry'){close} eq 1{close}Valid fruit{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if {echo $fruit | in('apple,banana,cherry')} eq 1}<p>Check: <b>{echo $fruit} is a valid fruit</b></p>{/if}

<h2>Chained Example</h2>
<pre>{open}if {open}echo $filePath | afterLast('.') | lower | in('txt,pdf,doc'){close} eq 1{close}Document{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if {echo $filePath | afterLast('.') | lower | in('txt,pdf,doc')} eq 1}<p>File type: <b>This is a document file</b></p>{/if}

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>Returns 1 (true) or 0 (false). The list is comma-separated with no spaces.</p>
